Cold temps and the first snow fall means being inside a lot which means times for low and slow cooking. ❄️I love Taiwanese pork belly baos because of the richness and delicious flavor. Instead of braising it over the stovetop, I opted for the sous vide method. Obvi, the @anova Precision Cooker Pro is my go-to! 

Taiwanese Pork Belly Bao

2 pounds skin on pork belly, cut into 2-inch thick pieces 
3 tablespoons dark soy
2 tablespoons turbinado sugar
2 tablespoons Shao-xing wine
2 teaspoons 5-spice powder 
2-inch piece ginger, peeled and thinly sliced 
1 teaspoon toasted sesame oil
1 star anise
2 tablespoons rice wine vinegar 
1 package of bao buns 
Pickled daikon, scallion, chili crisp for garnish

Set the temperature to 155 degrees F for 14 hours.

Place pork belly, dark soy, sugar, wine, 5-spice, ginger, sesame oil and star anise into a vacuum bag. Toss until combined. Seal until completely closed. 

Drop pork belly bag into the water bath and let cook undisturbed for 14 hours. Can be kept warm for up to 2 hours in the water bath before serving. 

When ready to serve, steam 8-12 bao buns until warm through. Remove the pork belly from the vacuum seal bag and transfer to a cutting board. Slice each piece in half and place on serving plate. Transfer the sauce from the bag to a small saucepan and bring to a full boil. Add rice vinegar and seasoning with salt and pepper. Let simmer for 10 minutes and pour over the pork belly pieces. 

Spread hoisin on the bao, top with pork belly, pickled daikon, and scallion. Drizzle with chili crisp and additional sesame oil, if desired. Enjoy!!!

✨2022 was a little tart and a lot of sweet just like a classic Lemonhead! 🍋Make this fun sparkling mocktail for the kiddies as they ring in the new year. Parents, you can also add booze if you want a nostalgic treat! 

1.5 cup Lemonhead candies
1 cup cold water 
1/2 lemon, cut into wedges
2 cups seltzer, water or champagne 
Star sprinkles for garnish 

Place 1 cup Lemonheads and water in a cup or jar. Let sit until most of the Lemonheads become white and the water is infused with the delicious lemony flavor, about 1 hour. This can also be made ahead up to 4 hours ahead of time. 

Take 1 /2 Lemonheads and smashed until finely crushed. 

Take 1 lemon wedge to coat the edge of the champagne flutes. Use plastic one for kiddies. Dip into the crushed Lemonheads. Pour about 2 tablespoons of Lemonheads syrup. Squeeze the remaining wedge of lemon into each glass, if desired for more tartness. Top with bubbles or water of choice. 

Garnish with star sprinkles! Cheers to 2023! 🥳🎊🍾

Happy Lunar New Year! 🎊
5 tot tips for the Lunar New Year Parade with my MomPush Lithe Double Stroller! 👶🏻👧🏻

😴Always have extra blankets. This makes a chilly day out a warm and snuggly one. Always perfect for nap time!

🙉Earmuffs are a must especially for babies under the age go 1. Fireworks, lion dance and confetti cannons are all fun but can be a little much for their little sensitive ears. 

🤧Wipes! All the wipes. Baby wipes, boogie wipes and alcohol wipes. Baby for butts and hands. Boogie for runny noses. Alcohol to sanitize.

🍎Snacks. Never can bring to make. Sweet and savory options are great. For sweet try to go for dehydrated fruit or fruit pouches. You can keep them in a backpack and place it in the basket.

🛍️Stroller hook. Perfect for any bags so mama can be hands free!

With this built in cup holder, you’ll be sure top stay hydrated. Now it’s time to spread good fortune for the year of the rabbit! Gong Hay Fat Choi! 🧧🐰

The cuisine of the Hunan province is one of the eight traditional Chinese cuisines, but what sets it apart from the others is its use of bold hot and sour flavors. Chiles, vinegar and fermented black beans are staples in Hunan cuisine, and this recipe uses all three. Hunan chicken originated in China and made its way to the United States in the 1970s, where the flavor profile was adapted to please the American palate. Here, bite-size pieces of chicken are marinated in soy sauce, making them tender and juicy, while vegetables are flash-cooked in a wok alongside other staples of Chinese cooking like garlic, ginger and scallions for a flavor-packed dish that hits all the tastebuds. Serve it right away, accompanied by fluffy jasmine rice. 

I can officially share the first recipe I developed for none other than The New York Times! Such a pinch me moment. 😍
Biggest thank you to my editors, Margaux, Melissa and tester Lisa. They made the process a collaborative and fun one.

Today is World Mental Health Day. Every year on October 10th, the world shines a brighter light on the importance of mental health. This year the subject is Mental Health is a universal human right and we should treat it as such. This video was part of a Mental Health and Motherhood campaign I wanted to share it with you all today. 
Personally the past year, especially in the past six months, has been a real struggle and I have been trying to heal and find ways to cope. Postpartum depression coupled with anxiety is a dark space. The first couple of months were the hardest. The hours were filled with endless streams of tears, healing pains, paralyzing anxiety of not being enough. Always trying to be the best and most as a woman, especially a mother was unbearable. One of the hardest nights was sitting in a hospital bed holding my infant, blaming myself for being a bad mom. Because I could not protect her from the germs that made her sick. All I could was hold her tightly and quietly sob as doctors ran test after test. That night broke me and drove me into the darkness of self shame. I knew I needed help and I could not keep these feelings inside. If I did,  it would take me from the inside out. 
I am extremely grateful for my husband, best friends and family for being around me. To show me love, to listen to my words and thoughts, to be present without judgement. Because of this support, I found the courage to seek a support group. To speak to fellow mothers about the internal emotional struggles as well as the never ending laundry list of tasks. I realized many of us share this burden and we must give ourselves and each other grace and love. 
Motherhood is an amazing journey but there are a lot of bumps along the way. Surround yourself with support to help you get back up or simply sit for a while until you are ready. 
You are worth it. You are loved. You are tough like a mother! 
XO Viv 

PS Check on your mamas

Not sure what to have for dinner tonight?  Check out my recipe for @nytcooking Sesame Chicken! Better than any takeout you can order. 🥡 

The history of sesame chicken, a delightful dish of battered and fried boneless chicken pieces in sweet and sour sauce, is a bit unclear. While it’s similar to General Tso’s, and la zi ji (or firecracker chicken), a spicy Sichuan dish of chicken, sesame, chiles and Sichuan peppercorns, sesame chicken skews sweeter, thanks to a heap of brown sugar and no chiles. As the name implies, the dish’s defining characteristic is the prominence of sesame flavor, owing to the toasted sesame oil in the marinade and the seeds sprinkled on top. Serve it piled on top of white rice and steamed broccoli. 

🤩 With gratitude to my VIP team @margaux_laskey @melissaknific & @lisanicklin for making this recipe come to real life. Styled by @cydmcdowell. Photographed by @christophertestani.

Lately, I’ve been hearing a lot about Orange Chicken from Panda Express while listening to the radio. It’s crunchy, savory and sweet. Just like my version for @nytcooking. Give it a try! Dinner made easy. 🍊🐔🍚

In 1987, chef Andy Kao and Andrew Cherng, a founder and chairman of Panda Express, developed orange chicken, a dish of fried chicken pieces coated in a sticky citrus sauce. The top-selling dish was inspired by a Taiwanese fried chicken dish, a Sichuan beef stir-fry with dried tangerine peels and the sweet-and-sour flavors popular in the Jiangsu region of China. In this version, boneless, skinless chicken thighs are coated in cornstarch, deep-fried until crisp, then tossed in a sweet and tangy sauce made with fresh orange juice. Adjust the heat to your preference with crushed red pepper, and serve over a bed of fluffy jasmine rice.

As always thank you to the team @margaux_laskey @melissaknific & @lisanicklin. Styled by @cydmcdowell. Photographed by @christophertestani.

Consider this a PSA to stop eating your Thanksgiving leftovers! I am so over turkey. Tonight  it’s all about Mongolian Beef. 🥩Quick, easy and delicious in only 30 minutes. Check out my recipe for New York Times Cooking. 

Despite its name, this simple stir-fry of sliced beef coated in a velvety and sweet sesame-soy sauce didn’t originate in Mongolia. Wu Zhaonan, a Chinese comedian who fled Beijing when the communist party took over in 1949, opened a tea shop in Taipei, Taiwan, where he served Beijing-style barbecue in which meat and vegetables are cooked on a high-heat griddle. Political reasons prevented the use of the Chinese city in the name, so he called it Mongolian barbecue instead. (Actual Mongolian barbecue is called khorkhog.) The dish eventually made its way to the United States in the 1960s, where restaurants made use of giant flat-top grills, often a focal point of the dining experience. This rendition of Mongolian beef calls for flank steak and uses soy, sesame oil, brown sugar, mirin and a significant amount of chiles. Serve it over a bowl of steamed jasmine rice to balance out the intense flavors.

As always, thank you to the team @margaux_laskey @melissaknific & @lisanicklin. Styled by @simoncooks. Photographed by @christophertestani.

Easy to make and belly-filling, these Chinese buns, baozi, are believed to have originated as early as 400 B.C. Unlike their bready cousins from other parts of the world, they’re steamed, not baked, which makes them pillowy soft and snow white. The classic size of the loaves is small enough to fit in the palm of a hand, but cooks have adapted the recipe to create different shapes to complement their favorite ways to indulge. One of the most common is to form the bao into pockets and generously fill them with slow-roasted duck, drizzled with hoisin sauce and garnished with cilantro sprigs. Whether the tops of the dough rounds are pinched shut or kept open like the clam-shaped bao here, nothing beats a fresh bao straight from the steamer.

🥳🐶Today is Coco Bean’s 13th birthday! Hooray for lucky 1️⃣3️⃣🙌🏽
A day to celebrate this little girl who’s been by my side since she was only 3 months old!
For the past couple of years, I have found it to be bittersweet as we celebrated another year around the sun for her. It’s no secret dogs can’t live forever even though they really should. However, I always thought that day was much further away. 
Back in early February when we went for an annual wellness checkup, but our world was shattered after a heartbreaking diagnosis.  We were informed that we have entered the last chapter of her life. Through the tears and fear, Jay and I made big lifestyle changes for Coco. Daily medications, time sensitive injections, balanced organic diet, monthly visits to the animal hospitals for tests and transforming our home to be safe for her loss of sight  were some of the major ones.  The vets would always warn us to be cautiously optimistic because time isn’t guaranteed. With this mindset, we’ve celebrated each and every day. Some days were simple with extra snuggles, some were more. Holidays and seasons changing were especially hard knowing that she may very well not be around next year. 
Truthfully, I have not let myself think about her birthday until the month of December arrived. The thought of any day without her hurts my heart so badly. Yet, I find so much gratitude that she is still here to celebrate this major milestone and countless others with us. Heartbreaks, celebrations, weddings, births, she’s has always been there right by my side through it all. 
I don’t know what’s going to happen in the new year or how much time we have left together but one thing I do know is that we made damn sure that she knows she is loved beyond measure each and every day!
Happy birthday my sweet baby girl! ❤️♾️🐾
